HRs remained elevated after adjusting for FRS (2.9 [95{\%} CI, 2.3-3.7] for men vs 3.0 [95{\%} CI, 2.0-4.4] for women). A low ABI (0.90) was associated with approximately twice the 10-year total mortality, cardiovascular mortality, and major coronary event rate compared with the overall rate in each FRS category. Inclusion of the ABI in cardiovascular risk stratification using the FRS would result in reclassification of the risk category and modification of treatment recommendations in approximately 19{\%} of men and 36{\%} of women. ConclusionMeasurement of the ABI may improve the accuracy of cardiovascular risk prediction beyond the FRS.},
